Markets in Europe drifted lower, led by German chemical company Bayer AG as a U.S. court judgement blamed Bayer’s weedkiller product Roundup for causing a case of cancer.
Investors were anticipating developments including the U.S. Federal Reserve’s press conference Wednesday and shrugged off conflicting rumours on U.S.-China trade talks.
German equities led the declines in Europe, with the DAX US:DAX falling 0.94% from Tuesday’s close to 11680.7, giving back Tuesday’s gains of 0.85%.
Aside from weakness in Germany, markets seemed broadly directionless in the absence of clarity on several fronts, including the Fed, trade and Brexit.
The company plans to nominate a successor to CEO Veronique Laury and is closing 19 stores in Germany, with more possibly to follow.